{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64c2f8bc-fea8-4f46-a8bb-fc4d9ac70a5f","content":"On macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT), you can still get a crash dump via the OS:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Configure macOS core dump location** — by default macOS writes cores to `/cores/`:\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/   # look for core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS may need SIP adjustments or the directory may lack permissions:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Re-run your app** and let it crash. Then inspect with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **Alternatively, use macOS crash reports** found in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` files contain stack traces and metadata automatically.\n\n6. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set the environment variable before running:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4   # full dump\n   ```\n   (NativeAOT may not honor these without `createdump`, but it's worth trying.)\n\n**Key takeaway:** Rely on the OS-level `/cores/` core dumps + `lldb` as your primary recovery path when `createdump` is absent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"69ee3c59-a4e6-4de7-b150-56c82160985d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository is empty, so I'll answer from my general knowledge about macOS crash dumps for NativeAOT apps.","outputTokens":422},"id":"15e98c32-cbb4-4d3e-88e3-298dffe2f231","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:03:46.548Z","parentId":"2a77617e-20bc-4a37-97b5-729fb566db1c"}
